06372nam a22006975i 9780773556225DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735562257 a10.1515/97807735562252doi  a(DE-B1597)657224  a(OCoLC)1078636623  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a261.8qOCoLC223/eng/2023112000aTurning to the World :bSocial Justice and the Common Good since Vatican II /ced. by Gertrude Rompré, Carl N. Still. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tEditors’ Note -- tAbbreviations -- tThe Spirit Lives On: Reflections of a Council Father -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tConscience, Freedom, and Humanism: New Foundations for Catholic Social Teaching at Vatican II -- tThe Social Mission of the Church: An Issue of Dialogue -- tMoralizing Neoliberalism? An Analysis of the Principle of Subsidiarity in Catholic Social Teaching -- tDialogue and Dignity: Linking Nostra Aetate to Catholic Social Justice Teachings -- tImages of Dealing with Social Injustice from Jewish Apocalyptic Tradition: A Resource for Renewed Reflection -- tA Voice from the South: Social Justice in the Latin American Church after Vatican II -- tTo the World: Ana Castillo’s The Guardians and Literature after Vatican II -- tAn Integral Vision of Peace? Assessing Catholic Social Teaching’s Contribution to Contemporary Green Cultures of Peace from Vatican II to Benedict XVI -- tThe Priority of Social Justice at the Second Vatican Council: Canadian Contributions -- tThe Search for the Common Good in Canada -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Second Vatican Council (1962–1965) was a watershed event in the history of the Catholic Church, a critical self-examination that sought at once to rediscover the most ancient sources of Christian thought and practice and to bring these traditions into the modern world. While few question the idealism and vision of Vatican II, its legacy is contested. Has the Catholic Church fulfilled the promise of the council? Has it successfully reclaimed the scriptural call to justice? Has it truly shifted its gaze to the "joys and hopes, grief and anguish" of our troubled world? Reflecting on both the vision of the council and its uneven reception, Turning to the World ponders the impact of Vatican II on interreligious dialogue, peace-building, and care for the environment. Focusing specifically on the Canadian and Latin American experiences, contributors work from diverse disciplinary perspectives to examine developments in the Catholic Church's understanding of freedom, conscience, and the common good. The volume also appraises the effects of the Church's turn to the world in its hope to voice the pressing needs of the human family, especially in contexts of great poverty and injustice and among peoples adversely affected by the modern and postmodern economies of greed. Exploring the legacy of Vatican II, Turning to the World offers a unique perspective on the influence, reception, developments, and applications of the council from the 1960s to the teachings of Pope Francis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and social problemsxCatholic Church. 0aSocial justicexReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aBaum, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackman, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolen, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo